ce:section.ce:para:
The presence of GQDs was confirmed from the HRTEM images (Fig. 1
                        a). As seen, the images show constellations of dual-sized graphene dots (Fig. 1b). It can also be seen that the dots are well-dispersed and possess nearly uniform shape with average sizes of 6.1 nm ± 1.8 nm (Fig. 1a and c) and 4.53 nm ± 1.045 nm (Fig. 1b and d) and an interplanar distance of 0.24 nm and 0.29 nm, respectively. The later matches the interplanar spacing of (1120) plane of graphene [21]. The existence of dual-sized GQDs is expected due to the unsynthesized nature of the GQDs which gives rise to a diverse carbon-rich environment. However, the exact mechanism of their formation requires further investigation. The dots also show a hexagonal structure, thus consistent with the expected hexagonal shape of a tiny graphene sheets [22]. Based on this, we confirm that the dots are graphene dots, not the amorphous carbon dots which is further supported by the AFM data (Fig. 2
                        ). XRD data (Fig. 1e) shows a very broad peak at 2θ = 26.52◦ which corresponds to the (002) plane of the carbon lattice which is in good agreement with other literature on graphene dots [23]. Based on this we confirm that the observed particles are GQDs, not the amorphous carbon dots.
